title: The Epstein Files and the Hidden World of an Unaccountable Elite
partialText: The search continues in the documents for ironclad criminal conduct, but the story of a sexual predator given a free ride by the ruling class has already emerged.

title: How The Times Is Digging Into Millions of Pages of Epstein Files
partialText: Two dozen journalists. A pile of pages that would reach the top of the Empire State Building. And an effort to find the next revelation in a sprawling case.

title: An A.I. Fight at the Pentagon, and Former Prince Andrew Is Arrested Over Epstein Ties
partialText: Plus, a lifesaving phone feature.

title: U.S. Imports Grew in 2025, as Trump’s Tariffs Reshuffled Global Trade
partialText: Data released Thursday by the Census Bureau showed the overall trade deficit with the world narrowed, the result of an expanding trade surplus in services. The trade deficit in goods was the highest on record.

title: Trump Mulls a North American Trade Pact Without Canada
partialText: U.S. officials are threatening major changes to a trade agreement with Mexico and Canada that could upend the way business is done and leave Canada on the outs.

title: Europe Worries About Another Trump Blowup, This One on Tech
partialText: Even as trade tensions between the United States and the European Union seem to calm, officials are concerned that a showdown is brewing over the bloc’s digital rules.

title: After Avalanche Warnings, a Sierra Nevada Tragedy
partialText: Eight skiers were killed and one other was presumed dead in the deadliest snow disaster in modern California history. Six were found alive.

title: In Lake Tahoe Avalanche Recovery, the Safety of Searchers Is Top Concern
partialText: Weather and snow conditions will dictate when the bodies of skiers killed in the avalanche near Lake Tahoe can be retrieved from mountain. More snow is expected.

title: Sugar Bowl Academy Says Multiple Victims Were Tied to Its Ski Resort School
partialText: Many of the people on the fatal trek had ties to a ski-focused private school, Sugar Bowl Academy, in the Sierra Nevada.

title: A Swiss Survivor on What It’s Like to Be Caught in an Avalanche
partialText: Heinz Mueller was buried under 30 feet of snow in the Swiss Alps in 1993 but made it out alive. “It’s panic,” he says.

title: In Devastated Gaza, Grandiose Peace Plans Clash With Reality
partialText: Israeli strikes on Gaza have killed about 600 people since a cease-fire began, according to health officials in the territory. Many displaced Palestinians are still living in tents. And there are some 60 million tons of war debris to be cleared.

title: Gaza’s Board of Peace: What to Know
partialText: President Trump’s new organization was established to oversee a Gaza cease-fire but has expanded its mandate. Critics say it could undermine the United Nations.

title: Alysa Liu Is Skating Again, Her Way This Time
partialText: At 16, out of love with the sport, Liu stepped away. Controlling her career, after years of oversight from her father, was the only way she could return.

title: As Trump Weighs Possible Iran Strikes, U.S. Military Moves Into Place
partialText: President Trump has given no indication that he has made a decision about how to proceed, as diplomatic talks continue.

title: Maps: Where the U.S. Is Building Up Military Force Near Iran
partialText: President Trump has not authorized military action in Iran, but the United States has built up its presence in the region in recent weeks. Now it’s sending even more firepower.

title: Where Things Stand on Witkoff and Kushner’s Negotiations Over Iran, Ukraine and Gaza
partialText: Iran, Ukraine and Gaza are in play as the Trump envoys conduct talks on all of them. But progress in each conflict is scant.

title: How Trump Is Making Sure His Ballroom Plans Sail Through
partialText: President Trump has installed allies — including his former receptionist — on the boards and commissions tasked with overseeing the project.

title: Russia Celebrated Him. Now He’s Accused of Having Troops Shoot Themselves.
partialText: A lieutenant colonel is on trial after being accused of skimming payments for battlefield injuries. He denies the specifics of Russia’s accusation but acknowledges engaging in a payouts scheme.

title: Dueling Protests at South Korean Ex-Leader’s Sentencing Highlight Political Rift
partialText: As a judge reprimanded former President Yoon Suk Yeol for amplifying political tribalism, demonstrators from warring camps blared slogans outside the courtroom.

title: Stock Slide and Slow Sales: What’s Happening in China’s E.V. Market?
partialText: Investors are selling shares of Chinese E.V. companies, concerned that intensifying competition and shorter production cycles mean the years of easy growth are over.

title: Ring’s Founder Knows You Hated That Super Bowl Ad
partialText: Since the commercial aired, Jamie Siminoff has been trying to quell an outcry over privacy concerns with his doorbell cameras.

title: Billy Idol Had It All, and Then He ‘Lit It With Butane’
partialText: Last year, the British rocker with the iconic sneer played his biggest tour yet. At 70, he’s revealing how he survived the tough times in a new documentary.

title: Assault on Sudanese City Bore ‘Hallmarks of Genocide,’ U.N. Finds
partialText: A paramilitary group in Sudan’s civil war “acted with genocidal intent” in a monthslong siege of El Fasher, according to human rights experts.

title: How Mamdani’s Income and Property Tax Proposals Could Affect New Yorkers
partialText: Mayor Zohran Mamdani has now proposed two options that called for raising taxes. Here’s a look at each proposal and the rationale and chances for each.

title: Lively v. Baldoni Tests What Crosses the Line on a ‘Steamy’ Movie Set
partialText: An affectionate slow dance. References to pornography. What rises to harassment on the set of a movie about a sexual relationship that turns violent?

title: Who Would Win Gold in the Coward Olympics?
partialText: There are a lot of potential contestants.

title: Our Favorite, Most Outrageous and Most Unexpected Moments of the Games
partialText: Three writers and an Olympic medalist on the grit and grace of the winter games.

title: The Board of Peace
partialText: Today we look at President Trump’s new diplomatic initiative.

title: Stephen Colbert Sizes Up R.F.K. Jr.’s Workout With Kid Rock
partialText: “The Late Show” host called the 90-second video of the two working up a sweat together “pure cinema.”

title: Defense Department and Anthropic Square Off in Dispute Over A.I. Safety
partialText: How artificial intelligence will be used in future battlefields is an issue that has turned increasingly political and may put Anthropic in a bind.

title: University of British Columbia Professors Sue School Over Political Correctness
partialText: A group of academics at the University of British Columbia say the school’s D.E.I. policies and practices, which include land acknowledgments, violate a law that requires universities to be “nonpolitical.”

title: New York to Back Away From Robotaxi Pilot Programs Upstate
partialText: Gov. Kathy Hochul had proposed expanding the programs beyond New York City, but they do not have enough support, her office said.
